<h3>Shepherding according to God</h3>
“Shepherd the flock of God among you…according to God…” (1 Pet. 5:2)

“Let no corrupt word proceed out of your mouth, but only that which is good for building up, according to the need, that
it may give grace to those who hear.” (Eph. 4:29)

In order to shepherd according to God, we need to become God in life, nature, expression, and function. We need to be
filled to the brim with the divine life, enjoying the Triune God as the fountain, the spring, and the river to become a
totality of the divine life, even to become the divine life itself. We need to become God in His attributes of love,
light, righteousness, and holiness. We need to be the reproduction of Christ, the expression of God, so that in our
shepherding we express God, not the self with its disposition and peculiarities. We need to become God in His function
of shepherding the flock of God according to what He is and according to His goal in His economy.

To shepherd according to God is to minister God to others. The Triune God is embodied in Christ and realized as the
consummated Spirit; this is the God whom we worship, proclaim, and minister to others. If we would minister God to one
another, we need to speak words of grace, truth, spirit, and life, ministering the processed God who has been wrought
into our being. (<i>Experiencing, Enjoying, and Expressing Christ (3)</i>, msg. 10, V.E.1-4, J.1-2)
<h3>The Living Vision of the Heavenly Christ</h3>
“And when they saw the star, they rejoiced exceedingly with great joy.” (Matt. 2:10)

The star is the living revelation, the up-to-date vision that human concepts can never teach. After receiving the living
vision, the magi were misled by their human concept and went to Jerusalem. When the magi were corrected by the
Scriptures and restored to the right track, the star appeared to them again; living vision always accompanies the
Scriptures.

The priests and the scribes had knowledge concerning the birth of Christ, but unlike the magi, they did not see the
vision, nor did they have the heart to seek after Christ. It is easy to accumulate scriptural knowledge, but if we would
have living guidance, we must live in an intimate relationship with the Lord; we must be one with Him. (<i>2025
	Thanksgiving Conference</i>, msg. 1, II.C, E, G.1; II.G.2,4)

The Scripture, the word of God, is the breathing out of God…The Scripture is the embodiment of God as the Spirit. The
Spirit is therefore the very essence, the substance, of the Scripture, just as phosphorus is the essential substance in
matches. We must strike the Spirit of the Scripture with our spirit to catch the divine fire. As the embodiment of God
the Spirit, the Scripture (God’s word) is also the embodiment of Christ. Christ is God’s living Word (Rev. 19:13), and
the Scripture is God’s written word (Matt. 4:4). (2 Tim. 3:16, note 2)

Let us pray for the Lord to always give us a heart to seek Him and live in an intimate relationship with Him. May He
make us those who regularly strike the Spirit of the Scripture to know the Bible and to have an up-to-date, living
vision.

Thank the Lord for His speaking to the churches during the past weekend’s Thanksgiving Conference on “The All-Inclusive
Christ as Revealed in Matthew.” Pray for the saints to receive, review, and assimilate the messages. All videos and
outlines are available at no charge until December 30 at <a href="http://www.lsmwebcast.com/" target="_blank"
